05029nam a22007815i 9781442683167DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20161996onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426831677 a10.3138/97814426831672doi  a(DE-B1597)465100  a(OCoLC)944177322  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aND237.N475bA77 1996eb 7aART0090002bisacsh04a759.1300aVoices of Fire :bArt, Rage, Power, and the State /ced. by Bruce Barber, Serge Guilbaut, John O'Brian. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (211 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTheory / Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tIntroduction. BRUISING THE PUBLIC EYE -- tDocuments -- tEssays -- tSymposium -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn 7 March 1990 the National Gallery of Canada issued a press release announcing its purchase of a large abstract painting by the American artist Barnett Newman for $1.8 million. Within 72 hours the gallery was under attack both for its selection of Voice of Fire and for the price tag attached to it. Objections came from across Canada and from all quarters.The Voice of Fire controversy was the most extensive and heated debate over visual art ever to have taken place in Canada. This anthology can be seen as a case-study, providing both a historical account of the outcome of the National Gallery's purchase of the painting and an understanding of why the gallery's actions provoked such strong opinions and feelings. In this volume the editors also address the peculiar and paradoxical character of abstract art in general and the problems it consistently poses for viewers. Newman's work is presented as the focus of these concerns.The attack on the gallery by the press, the general public, Canadian artists, and politicians is documented in the first section by a broad selection of cartoons satirizing the painting, press photographs, news releases, editorials, letters to the editor, and public exchanges. In the second section three essays offer contrasting accounts of the controversy and its significance. The first considers the social processes by which art becomes art, the second focuses on the role of the media in shaping public opinion about art, and the third compares the reception of Voice of Fire in two distinctive frameworks, first at Expo '67 in Montreal and then in Ottawa in 1990. In the final part four papers given at a symposium on Voice of Fire organized by the gallery in October 1990 (a combined effort at damage control and art criticism) are presented, as well as a transcription of the public dialogue between speakers and audience which followed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aArt and statezCanadavCase studies. 0aPainting, AbstractxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aPainting, AbstractxPublic opinion. 0aPainting, AmericanxPolitical aspectszCanada. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBarber, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuilbaut, Serge, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO'Brian, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Brian, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268316740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442683167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442683167/original  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACK